description: Store and retrieve data at any time from the web.

blocks.name: getBuckets
blocks.description: This endpoint returns a list of all buckets owned by the authenticated sender of the request.

blocks.name: getSingleBucket
blocks.description: This endpoint returns some or all (up to 1,000) of the objects in a bucket. You can use the request parameters as selection criteria to return a subset of the objects in a bucket.

blocks.name: getBucketAccelerate
blocks.description: This endpoint returns the Transfer Acceleration state of a bucket, which is either Enabled or Suspended.

blocks.name: getBucketACL
blocks.description: This endpoint returns the access control list (ACL) of a bucket.

blocks.name: getBucketCORS
blocks.description: This endpoint returns the cors configuration information set for the bucket.

blocks.name: getBucketLifecycle
blocks.description: This endpoint returns the lifecycle configuration information set on the bucket.

blocks.name: getBucketPolicy
blocks.description: This endpoint returns the policy of a specified bucket.

blocks.name: getBucketLocation
blocks.description: This endpoint returns a bucket's region.

blocks.name: getBucketLogging
blocks.description: This endpoint returns the logging status of a bucket and the permissions users have to view and modify that status.

blocks.name: getBucketNotification
blocks.description: This endpoint returns the notification configuration of a bucket.

blocks.name: getBucketReplication
blocks.description: This endpoint returns the replication configuration information set on the bucket.

blocks.name: getBucketTagging
blocks.description: This endpoint returns the tag set associated with the bucket.

blocks.name: getBucketObjectVersions
blocks.description: This endpoint returns a list of metadata about all of the versions of objects in a bucket.

args.name: delimiter
args.info: A delimiter is a character that you specify to group keys. All keys that contain the same string between the prefix and the first occurrence of the delimiter are grouped under a single result element in CommonPrefixes. These groups are counted as one result against the max-keys limitation. These keys are not returned elsewhere in the response. Also, see prefix.

args.name: keyMarker
args.info: Specifies the key in the bucket that you want to start listing from. Also, see version-id-marker.

args.name: maxKeys
args.info: Sets the maximum number of keys returned in the response body. The response might contain fewer keys, but will never contain more. Default: 1000

args.name: prefix
args.info: Use this parameter to select only those keys that begin with the specified prefix. You can use prefixes to separate a bucket into different groupings of keys. (You can think of using prefix to make groups in the same way you'd use a folder in a file system.) You can use prefix with delimiter to roll up numerous objects into a single result under CommonPrefixes. Also, see delimiter.

args.name: versionIdMarker
args.info: Specifies the object version you want to start listing from. Also, see key-marker. Valid Values: Valid version ID | Default

blocks.name: getBucketRequestPayment
blocks.description: This endpoint returns the request payment configuration of a bucket.

blocks.name: getBucketVersioning
blocks.description: This endpoint returns the versioning state of a bucket. To retrieve the versioning state of a bucket, you must be the bucket owner.

blocks.name: getBucketWebsite
blocks.description: This endpoint returns the website configuration associated with a bucket.

blocks.name: checkBucket
blocks.description: This endpoint allows to determine if a bucket exists and you have permission to access it.

blocks.name: getMultipartUploads
blocks.description: This endpoint returns a list of in-progress multipart uploads. An in-progress multipart upload is a multipart upload that has been initiated using the Initiate Multipart Upload request, but has not yet been completed or aborted.

args.name: delimiter
args.info: Character you use to group keys. All keys that contain the same string between the prefix, if specified, and the first occurrence of the delimiter after the prefix are grouped under a single result element, CommonPrefixes. If you don't specify the prefix parameter, then the substring starts at the beginning of the key. The keys that are grouped under CommonPrefixes result element are not returned elsewhere in the response.

args.name: keyMarker
args.info: Together with upload-id-marker, this parameter specifies the multipart upload after which listing should begin.

args.name: maxUploads
args.info: Sets the maximum number of multipart uploads, from 1 to 1,000, to return in the response body. 1,000 is the maximum number of uploads that can be returned in a response. Default: 1,000

args.name: prefix
args.info: Lists in-progress uploads only for those keys that begin with the specified prefix.

args.name: uploadIdMarker
args.info: ogether with key-marker, specifies the multipart upload after which listing should begin. If key-marker is not specified, the upload-id-marker parameter is ignored. Otherwise, any multipart uploads for a key equal to the key-marker might be included in the list only if they have an upload ID lexicographically greater than the specified upload-id-marker.

blocks.name: createBucket
blocks.description: This endpoint allows to create a new bucket

args.name: cannedAcl
args.info: The canned ACL to apply to the bucket you are creating. Valid Values: private | public-read | public-read-write | aws-exec-read | authenticated-read | bucket-owner-read | bucket-owner-full-control. Format: value1|value2|...

args.name: grantFullControl
args.info: Allows grantee the READ, WRITE, READ_ACP, and WRITE_ACP permissions on the bucket. Default: None. Example: emailAddress="xyz@amazon.com", emailAddress="abc@amazon.com"

args.name: grantRead
args.info: Allows grantee to list the objects in the bucket. Default: None. Example: emailAddress="xyz@amazon.com", emailAddress="abc@amazon.com"

args.name: grantReadACP
args.info: Allows grantee to read the bucket ACL. Default: None. Example: emailAddress="xyz@amazon.com", emailAddress="abc@amazon.com"

args.name: grantWrite
args.info: Allows grantee to create, overwrite, and delete any object in the bucket. Default: None. Example: emailAddress="xyz@amazon.com", emailAddress="abc@amazon.com"

args.name: grantWriteACP
args.info: Allows grantee to read the bucket ACL. Default: None. Example: emailAddress="xyz@amazon.com", emailAddress="abc@amazon.com"

blocks.name: putBucketAccelerateConfiguration

args.name: status
args.info: Sets the transfer acceleration state of the bucket. Valid Values: Enabled | Suspended

blocks.name: putBucketACL

args.name: grants
args.info: Array of json objects. The array of grantees. See README for more details.

args.name: cannedAcl
args.info: The canned ACL to apply to the bucket you are creating. Valid Values: private | public-read | public-read-write | authenticated-read. Default: private. Format: value1|value2|...

args.name: grantFullControl
args.info: Allows the specified grantee(s) the READ, WRITE, READ_ACP, and WRITE_ACP permissions on the bucket. Default: None. Example: emailAddress="xyz@amazon.com", emailAddress="abc@amazon.com"

args.name: grantRead
args.info: Allows the specified grantee(s) to list the objects in the bucket. Default: None. Example: emailAddress="xyz@amazon.com", emailAddress="abc@amazon.com"

args.name: grantReadACP
args.info: Allows the specified grantee(s) to read the bucket ACL. Default: None. Example: emailAddress="xyz@amazon.com", emailAddress="abc@amazon.com"

args.name: grantWrite
args.info: Allows the specified grantee(s) to create, overwrite, and delete any object in the bucket. Default: None. Example: emailAddress="xyz@amazon.com", emailAddress="abc@amazon.com"

args.name: grantWriteACP
args.info: Allows the specified grantee(s) to write the ACL for the applicable bucket. Default: None. Example: emailAddress="xyz@amazon.com", emailAddress="abc@amazon.com"

blocks.name: putBucketCORS
blocks.description: Sets the cors configuration for your bucket. If the configuration exists, Amazon S3 replaces it.

args.name: CORSRules
args.info: Array of json objects. The array of CORSRules. See README for more details.

blocks.name: putBucketLifecycleConfiguration
blocks.description: Creates a new lifecycle configuration for the bucket or replaces an existing lifecycle configuration.

args.name: rules
args.info: Array of json objects. The lifecycle configuration consisting of one or more rules. See README for more details.

blocks.name: putBucketPolicy

args.name: policy
args.info: Json object. Policy written in JSON. See README for more details.

blocks.name: putBucketLogging

args.name: targetGrants
args.info: Array of objects. Container for granting information. See README for more information.

args.name: targetBucket
args.info: Specifies the bucket where you want Amazon S3 to store server access logs. You can have your logs delivered to any bucket that you own, including the same bucket that is being logged. You can also configure multiple buckets to deliver their logs to the same target bucket. In this case you should choose a different TargetPrefix for each source bucket so that the delivered log files can be distinguished by key.

args.name: targetPrefix
args.info: This element lets you specify a prefix for the keys that the log files will be stored under.

blocks.name: putBucketTagging

args.name: tagSet
args.info: Array of objects. Container for a set of tags See README for more information.

blocks.name: putBucketRequestPayment
blocks.description: This endpoint allows to add a set of tags to an existing bucket.

args.name: payer
args.info: Specifies who pays for the download and request fees. Valid Values: Requester | BucketOwner

blocks.name: putBucketVersioning
blocks.description: This endpoint allows to set the versioning state of an existing bucket.

args.name: MFA
args.info: The value is the concatenation of the authentication device's serial number, a space, and the value displayed on your authentication device. Required to configure the versioning state if versioning is configured with MFA Delete enabled.

args.name: MFADelete
args.info: Specifies whether MFA Delete is enabled in the bucket versioning configuration. Valid Values: Disabled | Enabled. Can only be used when you use Status.

args.name: status

blocks.name: putBucketWebsite
blocks.description: This endpoint allows to set the configuration of the website that is specified.

args.name: indexDocument
args.info: A suffix that is appended to a request that is for a directory on the website endpoint (e.g., if the suffix is index.html and you make a request to samplebucket/images/, the data that is returned will be for the object with the key name images/index.html). The suffix must not be empty and must not include a slash character.

args.name: errorDocument
args.info: This key identifies the page that is returned when such an error occurs.

args.name: redirectHostName
args.info: The host name to use in the redirect request.

args.name: redirectProtocol
args.info: The protocol to use in the redirect request. HTTP || HTTPS

args.name: routingRules
args.info: Array of objects. Container for a collection of RoutingRule elements. See README for more details.

args.info: Return the object only if it has not been modified since the specified time, otherwise return a 412 (precondition failed).

args.name: ifNoneMatch
args.info: Return the object only if its entity tag (ETag) is different from the one specified; otherwise, return a 304 (not modified).

args.name: ifUnmodifiedSince
args.info: Return the object only if it has not been modified since the specified time, otherwise return a 412 (precondition failed).

args.info: Downloads the specified range bytes of an object. For more information about the HTTP Range header, go to http://www.w3.org/Protocols/rfc2616/rfc2616-sec14.html#sec14.35.
